<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Scope</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Scope</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scope remains </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">concerned that the payment of the housing element of Universal Credit (UC) direct to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tenants within their monthly payment will lead to increased arrears, and that changes to support for mortgage interest will equate to further cuts for disabled people.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Impact assessments have shown that changes to the uprating of Housing Benefit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(HB) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">entail huge losses for disabled people</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Penalties for under-occupancy in the social rented sector will have a grave impact on disabled people who either require extra space for needs relating to their disability, or are unable to move</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> house. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The cap on Annually Managed Expenditure (AME) will lead to inappropriate trade-offs between HB and disability benefits – meaning inevitable losses for disabled </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">people.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scope recommends that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4.1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Put in place proper provisions to ensure disabled people do not risk falling into arrears because of changes through UC</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4.2.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">econsider the zero-earning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s rule, and make provisions in light of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the barriers disabled people face in finding full-time employ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4.3. Make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exemption</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in regulations for disabled people living in specially adapted homes and those with legitimate reasons for being unable to move, or needing the extra space</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Put in place </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clear safeguards for disability benefits within the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> AME</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cap, so that disabled people’s incomes will have some protection against wider trends in the economy.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About Scope</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We all want to live in a world of opportunity – to be able to live our own life, play our part and be valued for the person we are. At </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scope we’re passionate about possibility.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It inspires us every day and means we never set limits on people’s potential. We work with disabled people and their families at every stage of their lives.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> From offering day to day support and information, to ch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">allenging assumptions about disability and influencing decision makers – everything we do is about creating real and lasting change. We believe that a world where all disabled people have the same opportunities as everyone else would be a pretty incredible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> place for all of us. Together we can make it happen.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For further information, please contact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ellie Brawn </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Public Policy Advisor), on </span><a href="mailto:ellie.brawn@scope.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ellie.brawn@scope.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Scope’s response to the call for evidence</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Universal Credit</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ost households, UC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will be paid a single monthly payment, with the housing element being directly paid to tenants as part of it. We remain concerned that this will have huge implications for disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> partly because they have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> been in the dark </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">about the changes affecting them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(In 2012 almost half (45%) of all disabled people had never even heard of UC) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– but largely because the change will affect the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">way those on extremely tight budgets will be required to manage their money</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The DWP has itself accepted that – even with the exceptions outlined in the Lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cal Support Services framework</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– the change from weekly to monthly welfare payments will increase the overall demand for advice.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Housing associations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have expressed concerns that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tenants will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> use the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">housing element </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of their U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C payment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to meet more pressing financial needs, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">meaning they fall into arrears.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">isabled people are experiencing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">considerable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">financial diff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iculties; Scope commissioned research </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">showed that nearly half (49%) disabled people are relying on credit to pay for the basics in life such as clothing and food, and are three times as likely to turn to doorstep loans (10% compared to 3% non-disabled people).</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Disabled people are also more vu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lnerable to financial shocks- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over a third (37%) say they could not afford an unexpected – but necessary – expense of £500, compared to a quarter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of non-disabled people (26%).</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This problem is therefore likely to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more acute for disabled people. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">National Housing Federation believes that the removal of direct payment alone could see arrears rise by £320million across the sector – a 100% rise based on our estimates of total rent arrears (together with a further £100million of additional transaction </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">costs).</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scope echoes the committee’s </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recommendation that the Government moves quickly to publish a clear</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">definition of "vulnerable" groups within Universal Credit for whom it will not be appropriate to include housing costs in their </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">benefit payment. It also needs to establish a robust process for proactively identifying claimants who are struggling to manage their housing costs so that they can be properly assisted before they fall into arrears and face eviction.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Changes to support f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">or mortgage interest through Universal Credit (UC)</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scope is concerned that the introduction of the zero-earnings rule for support for mortgage interest will disproportionately affect disabled people. The rule means that recipients will not receive any hel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p with mortgage costs if they are doing any paid work, no matter how few hours. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In their response, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment writes that “having a mortgage to pay provides a strong incentive for moving into full-time employment”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and that the rule will move people to “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re-consider their position with regard to the amount of work they do or the level of their housing costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Disabled people are more likely to be working in low-paid, short-term and part-time jobs</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wage gap </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">betw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">een disabled and non-disabled people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">remains higher than £1 an hour</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Many disabled people want to work - 1 in 6 would like to work more hours compared with 1 in 10 non-disabled people</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">- but face numerous barriers to the labour market</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These barriers include </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">housing; social care; other employment support; workplace culture such as employer perceptions; low confidence; difficulties accessing flexible working arrangements; fewer demonstrable skills, qualifications and experience than the w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ider population.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ut for those who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">face barriers to working more hours, or entering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">full time employment, the incen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tives </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for disabled people with a mortgage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are redundant, and will simp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mean </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more cuts to the support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">receive.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> urges the Government to reconsider the zero-earnings rule, and make provisions for the barriers disabled people face in finding full-time employment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Size criteria in the social rented sector</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scope remains deeply concerned that the size </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">criteria in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">social rented sector are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disproportionately affect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> disabled people. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since 1 April 2013, working age renters in the social sector have had their Housing Benefit (HB) reduced if judged to have a spare room.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If they have 1 ‘spare’ room their HB is reduced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by 14%, if they have two or more ‘spare’ rooms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> their HB is reduced by 25%. Tenants are faced with two choices – move to a smaller property or find a way to make up the shortfall. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The majority of those affected are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">660 000 people in total</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will be affected by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">size criteria </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by 2015, losing between £624 and £1144 per year. 420 000 (63%) of those af</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fected will be disabled people.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many disabled people need an additional room for specialist equipment; or so that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they can sleep separately </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from their partner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On top of this, moving house is not an option for many disabled people. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with mental health conditions find the thou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ght of moving very distressing; those with certain physical impairments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will find packing and moving house </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">impossible, and hiring someone to help, too expensive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disabled social housing tenants have been allocated their home on the basis of their needs, or have had adaptations made to improve accessibility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> With a lack of alternative accessible housing av</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ailable, these disabled people will be forced to pay more rent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On 30th July 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">judicial reviews brought by ten hou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">seholds against the bedroom tax, the high courts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">acknowledged that the Government is discriminating against disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The DWP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> argues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the £25 million in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Discretionary Housing Payment (DHP)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would cover the loss in HB experienced by those in ‘exceptional circum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stances’. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">danger that this cash-limited pot simply will not go far enough to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support all those that need it. Local Authorities will only be given a limited amount of money from which to make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">these payments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and so will have to make difficult decisions a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bout who to provide with a DHP, and for how long.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There should be an exemption in regulations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on the size criteria </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for disabled people living in specially adapted homes and those with legitimate reasons for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">being unable to move</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. There should also be exemptions for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">isabled couples who cannot share a bedro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">om </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ge for bulky medical equipment.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 126pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Housing Benefit and the AME c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ap</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cope is extremely worried about the Chancellor’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> announcement at the Spending Round that there will be a cap on the social security part of Annually Managed Expenditure - spending that the government has previously said could not be limited in advance, but now will be.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">State Pensions and JSA will be excluded from the cap, but disability benefits won’t be protected. Nor will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which – like JSA - respond to changes in the economy.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The impact of this is that disabled people are left exposed to trade-offs within the cap. So</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if one year the need for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rises sharply, there is a real risk that disability benefits will be a lower spending priority.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here is a substantial risk disabled people will lose out on vital financial lifelines.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We therefore want to see c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lear safeguards for disability benefits within the cap, so that disabled people’s incomes will have some protection against wider trends in the economy.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> February 2013, Universal Credit Local Support Services Framework, https://www.gov.uk/government/</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/181395/uc-local-service-support-framework.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> February 2013, Universal Credit Local Support Services Framework, https://www.gov.uk/government/</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/181395/uc-local-service-support-framework.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Scope i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">nterview with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">representative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> from Affinity Sutton group Ltd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">, June 